When will Lebanon's parliament give a vote of confidence to a new government? Hattip to @cm2310 for providing a window and framework to better understand this situation.

The time scope of the base rate for this question is extremely low. Lebanon has a history of taking a very long time to form a government and get a vote of confidence. Due to Lebanon’s sectarian power-sharing agreement, it is difficult under the best of circumstances to form a government within its sectarian political system. According to the Economist (https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2018/12/21/why-lebanon-struggles-to-form-governments), it took two and a half years for Lebanon to elect its previous president, “nine years to hold parliamentary elections, and 12 years to pass a budget…Lebanon has spent nearly two and a half of the past 13 years without a government.” Political talks in Lebanon have a long history of dragging on for months with little resolution.

When will Lebanon's parliament give a vote of confidence to a new government? Longer is more likely. Hattip @MJF20 and @OConnorNWC for their insights convincing me to weigh the out months more heavily.

Based on a number of articles (including those cited for this question), Lebanon takes a lot of time to form a government and this newly elected Prime Minister seems to be having the usual challenges in getting the support he needs. Therefore, it is more likely to happen later in the year than earlier.

Lebanon has recently gone years without a government and despite the current turmoil, deep divisions persist. https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2018/12/21/why-lebanon-struggles-to-form-governments

Over the last decade, governments haven taken from five to over ten months to form, with the most recent government taking eight months, reportedly with strong external intervention/support from France. The Hariri government resigned at the end of Oct 2019, placing the first window of success into March/April. While the new PM has vowed to speedily form a government, ongoing geopolitical tensions, lack of support from the movement that brought down the Hariri government (and their desire for technocrats in key ministerial posts), and lack of support from his own confessional sect, do not point to a speedy process. Nor does the PM’s likely inability to secure assurances of western financial support during a period of economic duress, given that Hezbollah is his main source of support.

I started off favouring something in distant future (beyond July 2020) and still feel that way but things could move quicker than I expect given rising dissatisfaction with status quo. Worth keeping an eye on this. From Economist: “A second successive night of violent clashes between anti-government protesters and Lebanese security forces left dozens of people wounded. Lebanon is currently facing its worst economic downturn in years and protesters accuse the country’s elite of mismanagement and corruption. Following the violence, the president, Michel Aoun, announced that formal consultations to select the next prime minister would be delayed until Thursday.”
The desert moves slowly.

The situation in Lebanon is much more complicated than it seems at first. The vote in 2019 was several years behind schedule. A lot of people put faith in the new government that they elected in early 2019 but it became obvious that nothing had changed after Saad Hariri's victory in the election.

Some background info from The Economist. All signs point to nothing quick and possibly something messy in the interim: “Lebanon repaid a $1.5bn Eurobond that matures today. For most countries that would be no big deal. But Lebanon borrows more than most. Its debt burden is expected to reach 155% of GDP by the end of the year. Its bonds are already rated as junk. Investors are increasingly worried that the government, which spends more than it brings in, will default. A dollar shortage adds to the sense of crisis. Economists say a plan is needed to restructure the debt and introduce structural reforms. Alas, Lebanon lacks the leadership needed to do that. Big anti-government protests forced the prime minister, Saad Hariri, to resign last month. (He has remained in a caretaker role, but ruled out a return.) The demonstrators now hope to bring down the sectarian political system, which breeds corruption. Lately they have clashed with supporters of groups, such as Hizbullah, that benefit from the status quo. Both politically and financially Lebanon is a mess.”

At the moment parliament isn't even meeting, much less figuring out a way forward. Given the gulf between protesters and traditional elites, I doubt the situation is going to calm down enough for anyone to form a government for months.
Lebanon is not a fast-moving country

This news article provides great background into what has happened and what will happen going forward. Since the resignation was accepted, a new government needs to be formed. Hence the "vote of confidence."

Factors going against vote of confidence to a new government in the immediate future (among others): 1. Demands from protesters - they have no faith in the existing political elite and the old guard 2. Past track record of government formation in Lebanon - long delays, political wheeler dealing, sectarian politics 3. Meddling by Iran to continue to destabilize the country 4. A candidate from the old guard is unlikely to be acceptable to protesters
